class Solution {
    public String mergeCharacters(String s, int k) {
        List<Character> res = new ArrayList<>();
        int[] win = new int[26];
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) {
            if (win[c - 'a'] > 0) continue;
            res.add(c);
            win[c - 'a']++;
            if (res.size() > k) {
                char drop = res.get(res.size() - k - 1);
                win[drop - 'a']--;
            }
        }
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for (char c : res) sb.append(c);
        return sb.toString();
    }
}


WRITEUP:
Using sliding window to maintain the frequency of characters in the result string.
if win[c]>0, same character sits k distance away, so we skip it.
when result>k, character at the start of the window is removed from the result and its frequency is decremented.


